## From Plan to Execution

Day 58 produced the Security Assessment Plan — the formal roadmap defining what will be tested, how, by whom, and in what sequence. Today the assessment begins. Task A-3 is the execution phase: the assessor works through the procedures defined in the SAP, collects evidence, executes tests, documents findings, and builds the foundation of the Security Assessment Report.

Today covers the technical control assessment work — the infrastructure review, the AWS configuration analysis, and the application-level testing that together determine whether the technical controls documented in the SSP are implemented as described and operating as intended.

I want to be transparent about an important context note before describing the assessment findings. The original version of today's content described findings — an unpatched Log4j library, a backup S3 bucket without encryption, port 22 open to 0.0.0.0/0 — as if they were discovered during the assessment. These were actually discrepancies found and corrected during the Task I-1 implementation verification in Days 54 and 55. In a properly sequenced RMF process, the assessor should not encounter those specific discrepancies because they were resolved before the assessment began and documented in the as-implemented SSP.

Today's write-up describes the assessment execution as it would actually unfold for a system that completed Task I-1 and I-2 thoroughly — where most controls are implemented as documented, some genuine assessment findings exist despite the implementation work, and the documentation provides the assessor a clear roadmap to evidence. This is the realistic picture of what a well-prepared assessment looks like.

