## What Actually Clicked for Me

The insight that clarified assessment execution today is understanding the difference between a finding and an observation — and why that distinction matters for how the SAR is structured.

A finding is a control that is not implemented as documented in the SSP, is not operating as intended, or is absent entirely. A finding represents a gap that requires remediation or risk acceptance. Findings are categorized by severity and drive POA&M entries or authorization conditions.

An observation is something the assessor notices that does not constitute a control failure but that they believe the organization should consider — a configuration that is technically compliant but represents a suboptimal approach, a process that works but has unnecessary complexity, a risk the documentation does not explicitly address. Observations are included in the SAR but do not drive formal remediation requirements.

The distinction matters because conflating observations with findings inflates the apparent severity of the assessment and may cause the AO to focus on minor issues rather than genuine gaps. A well-structured SAR separates findings from observations clearly, categorizes findings by severity accurately, and helps the AO understand the actual risk picture rather than a list of everything the assessor noticed.

