### AWS Config Compliance Review — CM-6, SC-7

**Assessor activities:** Reviews AWS Config rule compliance status for all rules defined in the monitoring strategy.

**Evidence reviewed:**

| Config Rule | Status | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| s3-bucket-public-access-prohibited | COMPLIANT | ✓ |
| rds-storage-encrypted | COMPLIANT | ✓ |
| restricted-ssh | COMPLIANT | ✓ (corrected in Task I-1) |
| cloud-trail-enabled | COMPLIANT | ✓ |
| iam-password-policy | COMPLIANT | ✓ |
| mfa-enabled-for-iam-console-access | NON_COMPLIANT | Finding — see below |
| ec2-ebs-encryption-by-default | COMPLIANT | ✓ |

**Finding A-3 (Moderate):** AWS Config rule `mfa-enabled-for-iam-console-access` shows NON_COMPLIANT for one IAM user. Review reveals a service account created for a monitoring integration tool that was provisioned with console access and no MFA. Service accounts should not have console access — they should use IAM access keys for programmatic access only. This service account was not documented in the SSP's IAM entity inventory and was not identified during the quarterly IAM review.

*Assessment classification:* Moderate finding. The service account with console access and no MFA represents both a configuration gap (console access should be disabled for service accounts) and a documentation gap (the account was not in the documented IAM inventory). If this account's credentials were compromised, an attacker would have console access to the AWS environment without an MFA requirement. Remediation: disable console access for the service account; add the account to the IAM inventory; review the quarterly IAM review process to ensure service accounts are included.

