## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While reviewing Finding A-3 today — the undocumented service account with console access and no MFA — I thought about the **2019 Capital One breach** from a slightly different angle than previous discussions.

The Capital One attacker exploited a Server Side Request Forgery vulnerability to retrieve temporary IAM credentials from the EC2 instance metadata service. Those credentials belonged to a role attached to the instance that had broader S3 access than it needed.

But a related vulnerability pattern — undocumented IAM entities with excessive permissions — is precisely what Finding A-3 represents. A service account not in the documented IAM inventory is a blind spot in the quarterly review process. If that account's access keys are compromised, the ISSO's quarterly review would not flag it as an account requiring scrutiny because it is not in the known-accounts list.

The quarterly IAM review is only as good as the completeness of the IAM inventory it is reviewing against. Finding A-3 reveals that the inventory maintained for the quarterly review missed a service account — meaning the review process has been executing correctly against an incomplete scope. This is an example of a control (quarterly review) that appeared to be operating per the SSP, but a deeper assessment revealed that the scope of what was being reviewed was narrower than intended.

This is exactly why independent assessment finds things that internal reviews miss — not because the internal reviews were careless, but because assessors approach the system without the assumptions the internal team has built up. The internal team knew what accounts they had created; the assessor started from the AWS IAM console and found everything that exists, regardless of what anyone thought was there.

